Background

In this lab, we will make use of the World Agricultural Supply and Demand Estimates (WASDE) published by the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA). The purpose of this exercise is to analyze the supply and demand for corn and learn how to estimate demand curves. The skills developed in this lab are readily transferable to other commodities. We will also introduce some basic time-series concepts that we will build on in the next lab.

Step 4 Relating Price to Corn Stock-to-Use Ratio

A common measure agricultural economists use to analyze commodities is the ratio of ending stocks (whatever supply of the commodity is left over at the end of the year) to total use (demand) of the commodity. Simply put, the stock-to-use ratio (SUR) tells us how much corn is left over as a share of all the corn consumed during the year. Mathematically, the stock-to-use ratio is calculated as follows:

\[ \begin{align*} SUR_t &= \frac{\text{Total Supply}_t - \text{Total Use}_t}{\text{Total Use}_t} &= \frac{\text{Total Supply}_t}{\text{Total Use}_t} - 1 \end{align*} \]

where the subscript \(t\) denotes the year. SUR is useful because it measures both supply and demand at a given point in time. An increase in corn demand (holding supply constant) will lower the SUR while an increase in supply (holding demand constant) will raise the SUR.

Create a new variable called SUR in your WASDE data frame using the above formula and generate a scatterplot to visualize the relationship between corn prices and SUR. Include a linear regression line in the scatterplot.

To calculate the SUR for each year using your WASDE data frame:

  • End Stock in the formula corresponds to the end_stocks column in your data.
  • Total Use in the formula corresponds to the total_use column in your data.

Linear Regression Analysis

Step 5 - Linear Regression and Diagnostics

Lets formally estimate the regression line shown in the scatterplot. The regression equation is expressed as:

\[ \text{Corn Price}_t = \alpha + \beta \cdot \text{SUR}_t + \epsilon_t \]

Estimating the Regression Model

We use the lm() command to run the regression and the summary() command to print the results.

The lm() function in R fits a linear regression model to your data.
The basic format is:

lm(response_variable ~ predictor_variable, data = your_data)

For example, to model y as a function of x in a data frame called my_data:

lm(y ~ x, data = my_data)

This will estimate the relationship between x and y by fitting a straight line to the data.

Calculating Price Elasticity

To better interpret this effect in percentage terms, we can calculate the price elasticity of corn with respect to the SUR. Elasticity helps us understand how responsive the price of corn is to changes in supply and demand conditions captured by the SUR.

\[ \text{Elasticity} = \frac{d\,\text{Corn Price}}{d\,\text{SUR}} \times \frac{\text{SUR}}{\text{Corn Price}} = \hat{\beta} \times \frac{\text{SUR}}{\text{Corn Price}} \]

Where: - \(\hat{\beta}\) = Estimated coefficient on SUR from regression - \(\text{SUR}\) = Average SUR in sample - \(\text{Corn Price}\) = Average corn price in sample

You can use the mean() function to calculate averages for price and SUR

# Calculate averages
mean_sur <- mean(WASDE$SUR)
mean_price <- mean(WASDE$corn_price)

In this formula, the first term ( ^ ) reflects the direct effect of SUR on price, while the second term is the ratio of average SUR to average price which scales the coefficient into percentage terms for interpretation

Question:
How responsive (elastic) is the price of corn to changes in corn supply and demand?

Non-linear Regression and Diagnostics

Step 6 - Non-linear Regression and Diagnostics

From the scatterplot, we observe that the relationship between corn price and SUR resembles an inverse relationship. We will estimate:

\[ \text{Corn Price}_t = \alpha + \beta \cdot \left(\frac{1}{\text{SUR}_t}\right) + \epsilon_t \]

Estimating the Inverse SUR Model

First, create the inverse of the stock-to-use ratio variable then regress corn prices on the inverse SUR.

# Create the inverse of stock-to-use ratio, run the regression, and examine the error terms
WASDE$SUR_Inv <- 1 / WASDE$SUR
reg2 <- lm(corn_price ~ SUR_Inv, data=WASDE)

summary(reg2)

Task: Use the gtsummary package to create a professional regression results table:

library(gtsummary)

This approach is reproducible and professional!

Elasticity Calculation (Non-linear Model)

Because we are estimating a different model, we cannot readily compare the coefficients from this non-linear model to the earlier linear model. Instead, compute the elasticity between price and SUR based on the non-linear model (at the sample average of price and SUR), and compare to the elasticity derived from the linear model. Remember, the elasticity formula will differ from the linear model (see below).

\[ \text{Elasticity} = \frac{d \text{Corn Price}}{d\text{SUR}} \times \frac{\overline{\text{SUR}}}{\overline{\text{Corn Price}}} = \frac{-\hat{\beta}}{(\overline{\text{SUR}})^2} \times \frac{\overline{\text{SUR}}}{\overline{\text{Corn Price}}} = \frac{-\hat{\beta}}{\overline{\text{SUR}} \times \overline{\text{Corn Price}}} \]

Question:
- How does this elasticity compare to the linear model?
- What does this imply about the relationship?

Time-Split Analysis

Step 7 - Estimating separate demand curves for different time periods

Return to our scatterplot of corn prices on the SUR. Lets break the data up into two time periods: 1973-2005 and 2006-2019. Using ggplot(), we can visualize how the relationship between price and SUR changed between time periods.

First we will need to create a character variable denoting the two time periods with the ifelse() command, then we will create a numeric dummy variable equal to one during the 2006-2019 period.

# Create a character variable denoting the two time periods, create a dummy variable for the post-2006 period, graph a scatterplot of price on SUR with unique colors and regression lines for each period
WASDE$period <- ifelse(WASDE$year >= 2006, "2006-2019", "1973-2005")
WASDE$P2006 <- as.numeric(WASDE$year >= 2006)

ggplot(data=WASDE, aes(x=SUR, y=corn_price, color=period)) +
  geom_point(shape=1) +
  geom_smooth(method=lm, se=FALSE) +
  ggtitle("Corn Prices vs. Stock-to-Use Ratio (19732019)") +
  labs(y="Corn Price ($)", x="Stock-to-Use Ratio")

Auto-Correlation Check

Step 8 - Check for auto-correlation/serial correlation

From the time series graph you made earlier, you can see that corn prices appear related over time, that is, they are likely lag dependent. Failing to account for this lag dependency means the residual errors will suffer from auto-correlation or serial correlation which can bias the estimated relationship between prices and supply/demand. We will explore this concept in much more detail in the next lab but for now, lets do a quick check for auto-correlation in the errors.

# Collect the residuals from the last regression, create a time series of the errors with a one-year lag of the error, then regress the error terms on the lagged error terms
error <- ts(resid(reg3), start=1973, end=2019, frequency=1)   # the ts() function tells R to set the errors as a time-series 
lag_error <- lag(error, -1)                                   # the lag() function creates a one-period lag of the error term
error <- cbind(error, lag_error)                              # cbind() binds the specified vectors together as columns to create a new data frame

reg4 <- lm(error ~ lag_error, data=error)

summary(reg4)

If auto-correlation is present, then the current error term will be correlated with the error term in the previous period, i.e., cov(e t ,e t1 ) =0 and we will need to correct for the lag dependence in corn prices.

Question:
Looking at the coefficient on the lagged error term, is there evidence for auto-correlation?

Understanding Functions in R

What is a Function?

A function in R is a reusable block of code that performs a specific task. Functions help you avoid repeating code, make your scripts easier to read, and allow you to update logic in one place.

R has many built-in functions (like mean(), sum(), plot()), but you can also create your own.

Why Use Functions?

  • Avoid repetition: Write code once, use it many times.
  • Clarity: Functions make your code easier to understand.
  • Maintainability: Update logic in one place instead of many.

How to Write a Function in R

The basic structure of a function is:

my_function <- function(argument1, argument2, ...) {
  # Code to run
  result <- argument1 + argument2
  return(result)
}
  • my_function is the name you give your function.
  • argument1, argument2, are inputs (also called parameters).
  • The code inside the {} is what the function does.
  • The return() statement gives back the result.

Example: A Simple Function

Suppose you want a function to add two numbers:

add_numbers <- function(a, b) {
  sum <- a + b
  return(sum)
}

# Usage
add_numbers(2, 3)
# 5

Example: A Plotting Function

Heres how you might turn your corn trend plots into a function, so you dont repeat code:

plot_corn_trend <- function(data, yvar, color, title, ylab) {
  ggplot(data = data, aes_string(x = "year", y = yvar)) +
    geom_line(color = color) +
    ggtitle(title) +
    labs(y = ylab, x = "Year")
}


# Usage
plot_corn_trend(WASDE, "corn_price", "red", "Corn Prices over Time", "Corn Price ($)")
